          "body": "Against the entire current of the chapter's first six verses, the adversative conjunction 'but' introduces the chapter's surprising hero (38:7). Ebed-melech the Ethiopian — a court eunuch, a foreigner, outside every circle of Jewish covenant identity and political power — hears the same information as everyone else and acts on it. His action has three stages: he goes directly to the king (38:8), he names the injustice plainly ('these men have acted wickedly,' 38:9), and he executes the rescue with care, resourcefulness, and attentiveness to the prophet's dignity (38:10-13). The worn-out rags for padding under the ropes (38:12) are a detail no writer would invent for effect — they are the kind of practical compassion that comes from genuinely caring about the person, not merely completing a task. The New Testament's logic of the outsider-as-model of faith has its deep roots here. Matthew's Gentile centurion, Luke's Samaritan leper, Mark's Syro-Phoenician woman — Ebed-melech belongs in this company. He acts in faith where insiders have acted in fear. Jeremiah 39:15-18 records the Lord's explicit promise to him: 'I will deliver you... because you have trusted in Me.'"
