          "title": "Custody and catastrophe — the word preserved, the city not",
          "body": "The chapter closes in verse 28 with a sentence of deferred resolution: Jeremiah remained in the court of the guardhouse until the day Jerusalem was captured. He is not freed; he is not vindicated; he is not silenced. He waits, in custody, for what the word had already described. The chapter's closing restraint is part of its rhetorical power — no dramatic reversal, no last-minute rescue of the city, no Zedekiah repentance scene. The word of God has been spoken (38:2-3, 17-18, 20-23), refused, and will now be fulfilled (chapter 39). What the chapter preserves in its final line is the prophet — still present, still in the city, still the bearer of a word that remains true after every human decision around it has been made. For the reader, the closing verse is an invitation to position oneself not with Zedekiah, who heard and refused, but with Ebed-melech, who heard and acted — or at least with Jeremiah, who spoke the word and endured the mud and waited for God to vindicate what he had proclaimed."
